    Most blockchains make you wait. Silica doesn't. Here's how we achieve sub-second finality and million TPS throughput.
  </p>

  <h2>Alluvium: Data Plane</h2>
  <p>
    Silica starts with <strong>Alluvium</strong>, the Narwhal-inspired data plane for transaction batching and dissemination:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High-throughput batching:</strong> Nodes create micro-batches of transactions (50-200 per second) and broadcast them as DAG vertices.</li>
    <li><strong>Data availability:</strong> Each batch is erasure-coded (Reed-Solomon) so any 2/3 of nodes can reconstruct the full data, even if some nodes are slow or offline.</li>
    <li><strong>Parallel processing:</strong> Batches propagate concurrently across all validators, not sequentially.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Result: the network is always accumulating transactions, not waiting for one block to finish before the next begins.</p>

  <h2>Tephra: Ordering &amp; Consensus</h2>
  <p>
    Once payloads are flowing through Alluvium, <strong>Tephra</strong> applies gossip-about-gossip consensus to produce a <strong>canonical global ordering</strong>.
    This is the network's ordering source of truth.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Leaderless ordering:</strong> No single proposer dictates order; commit rules select an unambiguous sequence.</li>
    <li><strong>Deterministic output:</strong> The committed sequence is the only ordering truth (no re-ordering later).</li>
    <li><strong>Byzantine-resilient:</strong> Safety holds under adversarial behavior; liveness resumes once the network can make progress.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h3>Timeline of a Transaction</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>T+0ms:</strong> Tx hits a Gateway node</li>
      <li><strong>T+50ms:</strong> Included in a micro-batch</li>
      <li><strong>T+150ms:</strong> Batch propagated, erasure-coded</li>
      <li><strong>T+400ms:</strong> Tephra produces a committed ordering</li>
      <li><strong>T+500ms:</strong> Crystallite applies the result in deterministic execution lanes</li>
      <li><strong>T+800ms:</strong> Lithification packages proofs and checkpoints</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Total:</strong> typically under 1s from send to finalized, checkpointed state. No confirmations to babysit.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Crystallite: Execution &amp; Apply</h2>
  <p>
    After Tephra orders the transaction stream, <strong>Crystallite</strong> applies that order in deterministic execution lanes.
    This is where pending becomes visible account state.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Deterministic lanes:</strong> Non-conflicting work executes in parallel without changing Tephra order.</li>
    <li><strong>Fast account updates:</strong> Balance and state changes become visible quickly.</li>
    <li><strong>No invented ordering:</strong> Crystallite applies Tephra order rather than creating its own.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Lithification: Proofs &amp; Checkpoints</h2>
  <p>
    Lithification packages finalized state into anchors, receipts, and replay-friendly checkpoints.
    It is the proof and checkpoint surface around the finalized chain.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Checkpoint packaging:</strong> Anchors and certificates make finalized state portable and auditable.</li>
    <li><strong>Proof surfaces:</strong> Receipts and certificates report the result without becoming new ordering authorities.</li>
    <li><strong>Recovery-friendly:</strong> Checkpoints make monitoring and restart flows straightforward.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Cali: Recovery &amp; Watchdogs</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Cali</strong> watches network health, detects stalls, and helps restart progress cleanly when conditions degrade.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Health monitoring:</strong> Tracks liveness, divergence, and node readiness.</li>
    <li><strong>Automated recovery:</strong> Helps the network recover without human babysitting.</li>
    <li><strong>Operational safety:</strong> Keeps the stack resilient under churn and partitions.</li>
  </ul>


